# Convert MovieLense to data frame for data Viz
MovieRate <- as(MovieLense, "data.frame")


#Most rated Movies 

most_rated <- MovieRate |>
  group_by(item)  |>
  summarise(total_ratings = n())  |>
  arrange(desc(total_ratings))  |>
  top_n(10)
## Selecting by total_ratings
ggplot(most_rated, aes(x = reorder(item, total_ratings), y = total_ratings, fill = item)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(title = "Top 10 Most Rated Movies",
       x = "Movie",
       y = "Number of Ratings") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

#Number of rating per user 
ratings_per_user <- MovieRate |>
  group_by(user)  |>
  summarise(num_ratings = n())


ggplot(ratings_per_user, aes(x = num_ratings)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 100, fill = "skyblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Number of Ratings per User",
       x = "Number of Users",
       y = "Number of Mvoies Rated")

#Number of user per rating movie

ratings_per_movie <- MovieRate  |>
  group_by(item)  |>
  summarise(num_ratings = n())

ggplot(ratings_per_movie, aes(x = num_ratings)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 100, fill = "red", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Number of Ratings per Movie",
       x = "Number of Movies",
       y = "Number of Users Rated")

#Avg user ratings

avg_ratings_per_user <- MovieRate  |>
  group_by(user) |>
  summarise(avg_rating = mean(rating))


ggplot(avg_ratings_per_user, aes(x = avg_rating)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.5, fill = "purple", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Average Ratings per User",
       x = "Average Rating",
       y = "Frequency") +
  theme_minimal()

#unique users and movies

number_of_user <- n_distinct(MovieRate$user)
print(paste("Number of users:", number_of_user))
## [1] "Number of users: 943"
number_of_movies <- n_distinct(MovieRate$item)
print(paste("Number of movies:", number_of_movies))
## [1] "Number of movies: 1664"
UMInteraction <- number_of_user * number_of_movies
print(paste("User-Item interactions:", UMInteraction))

#Examine similarity of items 


MovieSim <- similarity(MovieLense [, 1:5], method = "cosine", 
                               which = "items")

#Building a recommendation system using collaborative filtering

evalScheme <- evaluationScheme(MovieLense, method = "split", train = 0.7,
                       given = 12);
evalScheme
## Evaluation scheme with 12 items given
## Method: 'split' with 1 run(s).
## Training set proportion: 0.700
## Good ratings: NA
## Data set: 943 x 1664 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 99392 ratings.
#Training data 

train <- getData(evalScheme, "train");

known <- getData(evalScheme, "known");

unknown <- getData(evalScheme, "unknown");


User_Based <- Recommender(train, "UBCF")



pred_UB <- predict(User_Based, unknown, type = "ratings")
pred_UB
## 283 x 1664 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 133819 ratings.
#Evaluate model accuray for the unknown set of test users

accuracy_ub <- calcPredictionAccuracy(pred_UB, known)
accuracy_ub

## 1.1388849 1.2970587 0.8914056

#Creating a Item recommender using training data 
Item_based <- Recommender(train, "IBCF")



pred_IB <- predict(Item_based, known, type = "ratings")
pred_IB
## 283 x 1664 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 9491 ratings.
accuracy_ib <- calcPredictionAccuracy(pred_IB, unknown)
accuracy_ib
##     RMSE      MSE      MAE 
## 1.406981 1.979595 1.085125
acc <- rbind(USERBASED = accuracy_ub, ITEMBASED = accuracy_ib)
